  </section>

  <!-- Safety Section -->
  <section class="section-bone">
    <h2>Are Air Conduction Headphones & Earphones Safe for Your Ears?</h2>
    <p>Yes! Air conduction headphones and earphones are considered <strong>one of the safest audio devices</strong> available today. Because they don't go inside your ears or block your ear canal, they reduce the risk of:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong><a href="https://ngearsafe.com/blogs/open-ear-headphones/ear-infection">Ear infections</a></strong></li>
      <li><strong>Hearing fatigue</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Earwax buildup</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Discomfort from prolonged use</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>They're especially recommended for kids, older adults, and anyone using headphones for long hours. However, as with all audio devices, it's important to use them at moderate volumes to protect your hearing.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- Who Should Buy Section -->
  <section class="section-bone">
    <h2>Who Should Buy Air Conduction Headphones or Air Conduction Earphones?</h2>
    <p>Air conduction headphones/earphones are perfect for:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Runners and cyclists</strong> who need to stay alert</li>
      <li><strong>Commuters</strong> who want to hear announcements</li>
      <li><strong>People working in offices or remote</strong> who need to stay aware</li>
      <li><strong>Fitness enthusiasts</strong> who want comfort during workouts</li>
      <li><strong>Anyone who prefers natural, open-ear listening</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>If you value <strong>comfort, safety, and natural sound quality</strong>, air conduction headphones and earphones are made for you.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="section-bone">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    
    <div class="faq-item" style="margin-top: 24px;">
      <h3 class="faq-question">1. Are Air Conduction Headphones or Air Conduction Earphones Safe?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer"><strong>Yes! Air conduction headphones or air conduction earphones</strong> are safe for your ears. Since they don't block or insert into your ear canal, they reduce the risk of ear infections, hearing fatigue, and discomfort. They're considered one of the safest audio devices available.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">2. How do air conduction headphones work?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">Air conduction headphones work by projecting sound waves through the air toward your ears. The sound enters your ear canal naturally, where it vibrates your eardrum. These vibrations are then transmitted through the middle ear bones to the inner ear, where they're converted into electrical signals your brain interprets as sound.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">3. What's the difference between air conduction and bone conduction?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">Air conduction headphones deliver sound through the air to your eardrum, using the natural hearing pathway. Bone conduction headphones send vibrations through your cheekbones directly to your inner ear, bypassing the eardrum. Air conduction typically offers better sound quality and a more natural listening experience.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">4. Can air conduction headphones be used for phone calls?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">Yes! Most air conduction headphones and earphones have built-in microphones and work like regular Bluetooth headphones for phone calls. Many models feature noise cancellation technology to ensure clear calls even in noisy environments.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">5. Are air conduction headphones waterproof?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">Many air conduction headphones are water-resistant (IPX4 or higher), making them suitable for workouts and light rain. However, not all models are fully waterproof. Always check the product specifications for the IP rating to determine the level of water resistance.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">6. Do air conduction headphones sound good?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">Yes! Air conduction headphones deliver excellent sound quality. Since they use the natural hearing pathway, they can provide full-range audio including bass frequencies. Many users find the sound quality superior to bone conduction headphones, especially for music listening.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">7. Can other people hear what I'm listening to with air conduction headphones?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">At moderate volumes, air conduction headphones are relatively private. However, at very high volumes, some sound leakage may occur. This is generally minimal and shouldn't be a concern for normal use. Bone conduction headphones tend to have less sound leakage.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">8. Are air conduction headphones comfortable for long-term use?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">Yes! Air conduction headphones are designed for comfort. Since they don't insert into or block your ears, they eliminate pressure and discomfort. Many models are ultra-lightweight (some as light as 24 grams), making them ideal for extended wear during work calls, workouts, or casual listening.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">9. Can I wear air conduction headphones with glasses?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">Absolutely! Air conduction headphones are designed to sit comfortably around your ears, making them compatible with glasses. Their lightweight and ergonomic design ensures they don't interfere with your eyewear.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3 class="faq-question">10. When should I use air conduction headphones?</h3>
      <p class="faq-answer">Use air conduction headphones when you want to stay aware of your surroundings during outdoor workouts, commutes, office work, or walking. They're also great for people who prefer natural sound quality and want to avoid ear fatigue during long listening sessions.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

